There is no direct evidence that it was used by the Adoptianists‚ although if they had known of its exist· enee, it would have suited their purpose to cite more than one of its Christological passages. The Spanish commentator Claudius Taurinensis (t 839)¹ shews no traca of its influence in his exposi- tion of the Epistle to the Galatians. But if the Latin Theodore was circulated in Spain at all, it is at least possible that the work was executed in the Peninsula itself, the original having been brought thither direct from Constantinople.

Viewing the question then from an a priori standpoint, we qonctu· shall assign the translation either to the fifth, sixth, or seventh ΜΕ· century, according as we suppose its author to have been a Pelagiara a Semipelagian, an opponent of Justiniau’s edict, or a precursor of Adoptianism. ’

But this large field may be narrowed by taking into considera- tion the facts already ascertained with reference to the internal characteristics and early circulation of the work. Its latinity - seems to be of too late a type to justify the belief that it proceeded from a Pelagian or even a semipelagian writer anterior to the 6th century. Moreover it abounds in forms andconstructions strongly indicative of a North African parentage. The version of S. Paul’s Epistles with which its author was familiar contained such a large preponderance of Old Latin readings as to point distinctly to‘ the 1 same locality.
